<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-02-15T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-02-15T16:00:00-05:00" n="367" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d367">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111A.R.–N.C./48: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in the Dominican Republic</hi>
                                (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Ciudad
                                        Trujillo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-02-15T16:00:00-05:00">February 15, 1940—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 4:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>22. Department’s telegram No. 17, February 12, 6 p.m. The Dominican
                            Foreign Minister said that formal instructions to Pastoriza<note n="44" xml:id="d367fn1">Andrés Pastoriza, Dominican Minister in the United
                                States.</note> have not yet been sent presumably because of the
                            General’s absence on a high seas cruise, but reaffirmed in the most
                            positive way Dominican adherence to extending the powers of the
                            Neutrality Committee.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Norweb</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>